=== ACCESSIBILITY FEATURES (40 items) ===

--- TIER 1: HIGH IMPACT ---

1. aria-labels on all icon buttons (embed, expand-all, zoom, info)
   Screen readers previously read meaningless symbols like ⊖ and ⧉

2. lang="ar" (xml:lang) on all Arabic text elements in SVG nodes
   Without this, screen readers mispronounce Arabic text using English phonetics

3. Focus-visible ring styling with custom :focus-visible outlines
   Keyboard users had zero visual feedback when tabbing through the page
   Uses --amber color to match theme, with outline-offset for breathing room

4. Bumped --tx3 from #7a7268 to #8a8278 for WCAG AA compliance
   Previous contrast ratio was ~3.5:1 against --bg, now ~4.5:1
   Visually near-identical — slightly brighter muted text

5. aria-live="polite" on the detail card
   Screen readers now announce when dialect info changes on selection
   Used "polite" not "assertive" to avoid interrupting mid-sentence

6. Focus management: focus moves to detail card on open, returns to
   the triggering node on close. Essential for keyboard navigation flow.

7. Tab-focusable SVG nodes (tabindex="0") with Enter/Space activation
   All 13 main dialect nodes are now keyboard-reachable and activatable
   Each has role="button" and aria-label with the dialect name

8. Tab-focusable satellite nodes via MutationObserver on sat-layer
   Satellites are created dynamically, so a MutationObserver watches for
   new children and adds tabindex/aria-label/keyboard handlers on the fly
   Without this, expanded sub-dialects would be unreachable by keyboard

9. <main> landmark wrapping primary content
   Screen readers can now jump directly to the main content area

10. role="search" with aria-label on search wrapper
    Identified as a search landmark for screen reader navigation

11. <meta name="description"> for SEO and screen reader page context

12. aria-hidden="true" on all decorative SVG elements:
    - Glow gradient rect
    - Legend group (colors are visual-only, labels too terse for speech)
    - Ripple circles (.rip) on every node
    - Breathe animation circles (.bre) on every node

--- TIER 2: IMPORTANT ---

13. aria-pressed on toggle buttons (expand-all, zoom)
    MutationObserver watches class changes and syncs aria-pressed state
    So screen readers announce "Expand all, pressed" / "not pressed"

14. aria-selected on filter buttons (All, Classical, Eastern, etc.)
    Synced on click — screen readers announce which filter is active

15. role="tablist" + role="tab" + aria-selected on ref toggle
    (vs MSA / vs Quranic) — proper ARIA tab pattern for the scoring toggle

16. role="dialog" + aria-modal="true" on all three modals
    (info, feedback, embed) — screen readers treat them as modal dialogs

17. Focus trap inside all three modals
    Tab key cycles within the modal, can't escape behind it
    Handles Shift+Tab wrapping to last element
    Checks for focusable elements dynamically (works when button text changes)

18. aria-label="Close dialect details" on detail card close button
    Previously just × with no accessible name

19. aria-label="Send feedback" on feedback button

20. aria-label="Embed code" on embed textarea

21. <nav> with aria-label="Filter by dialect region" around filter pills
    Semantic navigation landmark for the filter button group

22. SVG role="img" + aria-label describing the map
    Screen readers announce "Interactive map of Arabic dialects..."

--- TIER 3: QUALITY OF LIFE ---

23. / key focuses search (like GitHub)
    Only when not already in an input/textarea, prevents conflict

24. Enter in search selects first visible match
    Finds first .dnode:not(.dim) and clicks it

25. No-results indicator (#no-results div)
    Shows "No dialects match your search" when search filters to zero matches
    Previously just dimmed everything with no text feedback

26. autocapitalize="none" on search input
    Prevents iOS from capitalizing first letter of dialect searches

27. spellcheck="false" on search input
    Prevents red squiggles on dialect names like "Sana'ani"

28. Screen reader text for difficulty dots
    The d-dlabel element gets aria-label matching its text content
    So "3/5 vs Modern Standard Arabic" is properly announced

29. prefers-reduced-motion (from previous commit, still active)
    Kills all animations and transitions for users with that OS setting

30. overflow-x:hidden on svg-wrap
    Prevents any horizontal scroll on narrow viewports

=== ERRORS AVERTED ===

1. Triple monkey-patching showDetail
   The bottom sheet IIFE already patches showDetail, and the accessibility
   IIFE patches it again. Each layer calls the previous version maintaining
   the chain: original → bottom sheet (backdrop, scroll lock) → accessibility
   (focus management). Breaking this chain would silently lose features.

2. <main> replacing <div id="wrap">
   All CSS selectors use #wrap which works on any element type, so the
   element change is safe. But the closing </div> had to change to </main>
   — a mismatch would break the DOM tree.

3. Focus trap vs Escape handler
   The focus trap only intercepts Tab key, doesn't interfere with the
   separate Escape handler. Without this separation, Escape could get
   swallowed by the trap.

4. MutationObserver on dynamically created satellites
   Without observing sat-layer for childList changes, any satellite nodes
   created after page load would be invisible to keyboard users. The
   observer fires on every expansion and adds accessibility attributes.

5. aria-live="polite" not "assertive"
   "assertive" would interrupt whatever the screen reader is currently
   saying, which is jarring. "polite" waits for a natural pause.

6. --tx3 contrast bump is minimal
   #7a7268 → #8a8278 is only 16 units brighter per channel. Enough to
   cross WCAG AA but not enough to visually alter the design language.
   Tested that no text becomes too bright or loses its "muted" character.

7. autocapitalize="none" prevents iOS search friction
   iOS auto-capitalizes the first character in inputs by default. For a
   search that filters on lowercase comparison this doesn't break anything,
   but it's confusing UX when "E" appears and the user typed "egyptian".

8. nav element replacing div for .fbtn-row
   CSS used display:contents on desktop (element invisible to layout) and
   display:flex on mobile. Both work identically on <nav> as on <div>.
   The .fbtn querySelectorAll('.fbtn') calls still find the buttons inside
   the nav element — no selector breakage.
